Here's an example of how you can create a simple search bar using PHP and HTML. This will include a form with a text input for the user to enter their search query, and a submit button to send the request to the server.

**index.php**
```php
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Search Bar</title>
    <style>
        /* Add some basic styling */
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
        }
        form {
            width: 50%;
            margin: 20px auto;
            padding: 10px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            border-radius: 5px;
            box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2);
        }
        input[type="text"] {
            width: 100%;
            height: 40px;
            padding: 10px;
            font-size: 16px;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 5px;
            box-shadow: inset 0 0 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2);
        }
        button[type="submit"] {
            width: 100%;
            height: 40px;
            background-color: #4CAF50;
            color: #fff;
            padding: 10px;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 5px;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <form action="search.php" method="get">
        <input type="text" name="q" placeholder="Search...">
        <button type="submit">Search</button>
    </form>

    <?php
    // If the search query is set, display a message with the results
    if (isset($_GET['q'])) {
        echo "<h2>Search Results:</h2>";
        $searchQuery = $_GET['q'];
        // Here you can insert your own database logic to fetch data based on the search query
        // For now, we'll just display a simple message with the search query
        echo "You searched for: <b>$searchQuery</b><br><br>";
    }
    ?>
</body>
</html>
```
**search.php**
```php
<?php
// This script will handle the search request from the form above

// Check if the search query is set in the URL
if (isset($_GET['q'])) {
    $searchQuery = $_GET['q'];
    // Here you can insert your own database logic to fetch data based on the search query
    // For now, we'll just display a simple message with the search query
    echo "You searched for: <b>$searchQuery</b><br><br>";
} else {
    // If no search query is set, redirect back to the index page
    header("Location: index.php");
    exit();
}
?>
```
**How it works**

1. The user types a search query into the input field on the index page.
2. When the user clicks the "Search" button, the form data (in this case, just the search query) is sent to the server via an HTTP GET request.
3. The `search.php` script checks if a search query has been set in the URL using `isset($_GET['q'])`.
4. If a search query has been set, the script displays a message with the search query (or you can insert your own database logic to fetch data based on the search query).
5. If no search query is set, the script redirects back to the index page.

Note: This is a very basic example and in a real-world application, you would want to handle errors, security concerns, and optimize performance as needed.

